Stack and heap are two distinct areas of RAM, and provide different characteristic.

Stack Memory (Local & Fast)
Purpose: Stores local variables, function parameters, and return addresses.
Access: Very fast access, cache-friendly.
Lifespan: Data is created when a function is called and automatically deleted when it returns. ( This is about stack frame )
Organization: Strict LIFO structure (like a pile of books).

Heap Memory (Dynamic & Flexible) 
Purpose: Stores objects, arrays, and data that require a longer lifespan or dynamic sizing (e.g., new objects in Java/C++).
Access: Slower than the stack.
Lifespan: Data exists until it is explicitly freed (like free in C) or removed by a garbage collector.
Organization: No strict order, dispersed throughout memory (can lead to fragmentation).

